@article{Dutta2014,
abstract = {Internet has grown exponentially over the years; it hasunder its ambit, enormous amount of information and data in almost all domains and subjects, and is ever expanding. This unprecedented expansion has created problems for the users to retrieve useful information from internet and ignore the useless ones.Recommender systems are meant to be an important solution to the data overload problem that persists today in World Wide Web and is meant to be an important tool that aids the user in filtering the relevant useful information and weed out the unnecessary part. Very recent research trend in Recommender systemsencourages towards consideration of Context awareness.One of the major challenges in the context aware recommender system is the determination of proper granularity for relevant contexts so that the accuracy of the recommender system improves. If the context granularity is very small, that is the context parameters are too granular, the data points matching the contexts reduces. Context granularity is too large; contexts become generic and the level of context matching reduces. In both the cases, the overall accuracy of the recommender system suffers and in-turn negatively affects the usability of the recommender system. Contexts in recommender system comprised of „n‟ contextual attributes and the domain of each contextual attribute forms an ordered hierarchy of level of abstraction. It is advantageous if the contexts attributes are hierarchically divided into finer granularity and calculate the similarity between the target contexts with the nearest context attribute. In this paper, we propose an approach and a model,thatcalculatesthe similarities for the context attributes of relevant contexts. If the similarity values are within a predefined range then those are used in trust calculations and neighbourhood formation. This approach is advantageous in terms of increased recommender accuracy and also overcome data sparseness of hard context filtering methods.},
